05569nam a22007455i 9780674273818DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742738187 a10.4159/97806742738182doi  a(DE-B1597)613886  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQL673 7aNAT0430002bisacsh04a598.147/222300aBird Coloration, Volume 2 :bFunction and Evolution /ced. by Geoffrey E. Hill. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (528 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. Function -- t1. Natural Selection and Coloration: Protection, Concealment, Advertisement, or Deception? -- t2. Intraspecific Variation in Coloration -- t3. Color Displays as Intrasexual Signals of Aggression and Dominance -- t4. Female Mate Choice for Ornamental Coloration -- t5. Function and Evolution of Color in Young Birds -- t6. Benefits to Females of Assessing Color Displays -- t7. Female Coloration: Review of Functional and Nonfunctional Hypotheses -- tII. Evolution -- t8. Colorful Phenotypes of Colorless Genotypes: Toward a New Evolutionary Synthesis of Color Displays -- t9. Ecological Explanations for Interspecific Variability in Coloration -- t10. Adding Color to the Past: Ancestral-State Reconstruction of Coloration -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tSpecies Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this companion volume to Bird Coloration: Volume 1, Mechanisms and Measurements, Geoffrey E. Hill and Kevin J. McGraw have assembled some of the world's leading experts in the function and evolution of bird coloration to contribute to a long-overdue synthesis of a burgeoning field of inquiry. In Volume 2, the authors turn from the problem of how birds see and produce color and how researchers measure it, to what is the function of the colorful displays of birds and what are the factors that shape the evolution of color signals. The contributors to this volume begin by examining the function of coloration in a variety of contexts from mate choice, to social signaling, to individual recognition, synthesizing a vast amount of recent findings by researchers around the world. The volume and the series conclude with chapters that consider coloration from an explicitly evolutionary perspective, examining selective pressures that have led to the evolution of colors and patterns on body and plumage. These functional and evolutionary studies build from research on mechanisms of production and controls of expression, covered in the previous volume, bringing the study of color full circle. This sumptuously illustrated book will be essential reading for biologists studying animal coloration, but it will also be treasured by anyone curious about why birds are colorful and how they got that way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aBirdsxColor. 7aNATURE / Animals / Birds.2bisacsh1 aAmundsen, Trond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadyaev, Alexander V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBortolotti, Gary R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Simon C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Geoffrey E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Geoffrey E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHofmann, Christopher M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKilner, Rebecca M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary